                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13903528" author="lhofhansl" created="Mon, 17 Feb 2014 21:46:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I usually just copy the release nodes from jira &quot;Release Notes&quot; link. Could probably use the jira API.&lt;br/&gt;
Not sure it&apos;s worth the effort, would still need to commit the changes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(And sorry I missed that in the review of the 0.98RCs; CHANGES.txt should always be updated)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13903577" author="apurtell" created="Mon, 17 Feb 2014 22:48:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Good point, not &apos;release&apos; profile but something like what we do for regenerating protobuf.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13904700" author="stack" created="Tue, 18 Feb 2014 22:19:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I copy from JIRA but then have to do vim hackery to make them fit the CHANGES.txt.  IIRC, JIRA has upper bound of 100 JIRAs at a time which is a PITA so in the past had to get a 100 at a time.  I&apos;ve been putting the URL for the JIRA release into the CHANGES.txt.  This has a downside in that JIRA is the authority and cannot be &apos;damaged&apos; (I suppose we should &apos;close&apos; issues as soon as release is done so they are no longer editable up in JIRA).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13904705" author="lhofhansl" created="Tue, 18 Feb 2014 22:23:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The release notes link shows everything, no? (too long in 0.94 land with &amp;lt; 50 changes per release &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; )&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13904720" author="apurtell" created="Tue, 18 Feb 2014 22:32:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I sent out a release notes link with the 0.98.0 release announcement. JIRA will produce them on demand for the curious. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Why not simply nuke CHANGES.txt?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13904754" author="lhofhansl" created="Tue, 18 Feb 2014 23:00:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think it&apos;s nice to have the authoritative changes as part of the release. Jira might go away or have issues (or Stack might delete all the version tags &lt;b&gt;smile&lt;/b&gt;).&lt;br/&gt;
It&apos;s not really that much work to cut and paste from the release notes into CHANGES.txt and then commit that file. Just my $0.02. I&apos;m fine either way.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13904769" author="stack" created="Tue, 18 Feb 2014 23:10:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I do like it when Lars puts the issues fixed into the email he sends out announcing the release (Works when you have not too many issues).  A little script that formatted for CHANGES.txt from JIRA release notes would be sweet (I should have a go at it....)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13904833" author="enis" created="Tue, 18 Feb 2014 23:54:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I am happy to test it &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13994792" author="apurtell" created="Mon, 12 May 2014 04:32:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Going with what Lars said above, resolving as not a problem&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
